Exercise 1
¶

In this exercise you will learn how to use a variety of radiation laws to compute:
The Sun's Emissive power at the surface of the sun, at the top of the Erth's atmosphere, and any angle of incidence

Theory

The sun is actually much hotter on the inside, but we can approximate its surface, at which the emission takes place, as a blackbody at a temperature of about 5780 $^o$K (numbers around 6000$^o$K are used sometimes too).

The Stefan-Boltzmann equation¶

This equation gives us the energy flux emitted at the sun’s surface:

M$_s$ = σ.T$^4$ [Eq. 1]

Where:

σ = 5.6697 × 10$^{-8}$ W·m$^{-2}$·K$^{-4}$, and
T = 5780$^o$K

Inverse Square Distance Law¶

As this energy propagates through outerspace towards the Earth it weakens as it needs to cover much larger areas and volumes. It will spread over larger spherical surfaces as it travels outward. The intensity of this radiation decays proportionally to:

$\frac{1}{r^2}$ [Eq. 2]

Where :

r : is the distance away from the source.

Cosine Law¶

The Lambert's cosine law states that the radiant intensity is directly proportional to the cosine of the angle θ between the direction of the incident light and the surface normal. As the angle of incidence changes from 90$^o$ (normal angle) the less effective the transmission. This leads to the simple equation that says:

Eθ = E. cos(θ) [Eq. 3]

With these three Equations, you can estimate the incident irradiance at any point in space at any angle.

Derive the (model) Curve of the Cosine Law¶
